<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="prep-9-28">
  <title>Resources for 9/28</title>

  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Given formulas for two functions <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>, determine a formula for the function <m>f \circ g</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Given the graph of two functions <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>, compute <m>(f \circ g)(x)</m> for given values of <m>x</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Explain and use the definition of <em>inverse functions</em>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Given the formula for a function <m>f</m>, determine the formula for the inverse function <m>f^{-1}</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-composition">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Composition of Functions</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on <em>composition of functions</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="JWw_wuxT7o0" />

    <example>
      <title>Composition of Functions</title>
      <p>
        Solve the following problems on composition of functions.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find <m>f \circ g</m> and <m>g \circ f</m> for each of the following.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>f(x) = 2x+3</m>, <m>g(x) = \sqrt{x^3+3x}</m>
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>f(x)=x^2+x</m>, <m>g(x)=\frac{x}{x+1}</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              For each of the following <m>f: \mathbb{R} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m>, decompose <m>f</m> into as many functions (actions) as possible.  Describe these functions both as actions and as formulas.  Also, write <m>f</m> as a composition of these functions.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>f(x)=5x-6</m>
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>f(x) = 3x^3+11</m>
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>f(x) = \sqrt{\frac{x^2+1}{5}}</m>
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Consider the graphs for functions <m>p</m> and <m>q</m>.
            </p>
            <image width="60%">
      	      <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="composition-graph-prep">
                <diagram dimensions="(300, 300)" margins="5">
                  <definition>f(x)=-2*x-3</definition>
                  <definition>g(x)=0.5*(x+1)-1</definition>
                  <definition>h(x)=2*(x-1)</definition>
                  <definition>k(x)=3*(x+1)+2</definition>
                  <definition>m(x)=2</definition>
                  <definition>n(x)=-x+3</definition>
                  <coordinates bbox="(-4,-4,4,4)">
                    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y" hticks="(-1,1,5)" vticks="(-1,1,5)" spacings="((-4,0.5,4),(-4,0.5,4))" />
                    <graph function="f" domain="(-4,-1)" />
                    <graph function="g" domain="(-1,1)" />
                    <graph function="h" domain="(1,4)" />
                    <graph function="k" domain="(-4,-1)" stroke="green" />
                    <graph function="m" domain="(-1,1)" stroke="green" />
                    <graph function="n" domain="(1,4)" stroke="green" />
                    <label anchor="(-3,3)" alignment="ne"> <m>p</m> </label>
                    <label anchor="(-2.5,-2.5)" alignment="nw"> <m>q</m> </label>
                  </coordinates>
                </diagram>
              </prefigure>
            </image>
            <p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Pick some integer values of <m>x</m> and compute <m>p(q(x))</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Pick some integer values of <m>x</m> and compute <m>q(p(x))</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find <m>f \circ g</m> for the functions <m>f: \{ -3,-1,1,2,3,5 \} \rightarrow \{3,7,9,10 \}</m> and <m>g: \{ 1,2,4,5,6,10 \} \rightarrow \{ -3,1,2,3,5 \}</m> given by <md>f = \{(1,3),(5,7),(2,3),(3,9),(-1,7),(-3,10)\}</md> <md>g=\{(5,2),(1,3),(4,1),(6,-3),(2,1),(10,5)\}</md>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-intro-inverse">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Introduction to Inverse Functions</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video introducing <em>inverse functions</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="px0-Wo2QVrk" />

    <example>
      <title>Introduction to Inverse Functions</title>
      <p>
        Solve the following introductory inverse function problems.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              If possible, find the inverse for each of the following functions.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>f(x)=5x-6</m>
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>f(x) = 3x^3+11</m>
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Define the functions <m>f: \{ -3,-1,1,2,3,5 \} \rightarrow \{3,7,9,10 \}</m> and <m>g: \{ 1,2,4,5,6,10 \} \rightarrow \{ -3,1,2,3,5,7 \}</m> by 
              <md>f = \{(1,3),(5,7),(2,3),(3,9),(-1,7),(-3,10)\},</md>
              <md>g=\{(5,2),(1,3),(4,1),(6,-3),(2,7),(10,5)\}</md>
        Note that for each function, the first coordinate of each ordered pair is the input and the second is the output.  Find <m>f^{-1}</m> and/or <m>g^{-1}</m>, if possible.  In other words, try to find functions that cancel <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>, respectively.  Determine the domain and range of the inverse function(s).
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find the inverse, if possible, for <m>f(x)=x^2</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

